{"title_page": "Angie Martinez", "text_new": "{{BLP sources|date=March 2011}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name = Angie Martinez\n| alias = The Voice of New York\n| background = solo_singer\n| birth_name = Angela Martinez\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|mf=yes|1971|1|9}}\n| birth_place =[[Brooklyn, New York|Brooklyn]], [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U. S.\n| genre = [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n| occupation = [[Radio personality]], \n| years_active = 1992\u2013present\n| label = [[Elektra Records]], [[Roc Nation]]\n| website = [http://www.theangiemartinezshow.com/ TheAngieMartinezShow.com]\n}}\n\n'''Angela Martinez''' (born January 9, 1971) is an [[United States|American]] radio personality, rapper, and actress of Puerto Rican, Cuban and Dominican heritage.<ref>[https://www.amny.com/news/hispanic-heritage-month-7-nyc-power-players-1.9485464] {{dead link|date=January 2020}}</ref> Nicknamed \u201cThe Voice of New York\u201d, her afternoon radio show has consistently been ranked #1 with more young listeners than any other radio program in the country.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.latintrends.com/happy-birthday-angie-martinez/ |title=Happy Birthday, Angie Martinez! |website=Latintrends.com |date=2012-01-09 |accessdate=2016-02-26}}</ref>\n\n==Radio career==\nAngie Martinez got her first break in radio at the age of 16 answering hot lines at the urban radio station [[WQHT]] (\"Hot 97\"). There she met popular DJ [[Funkmaster Flex]], and began working as his prot\u00e9g\u00e9. Martinez quickly picked up on the craft of running a successful radio program. She hosted the Afternoon Drive weekdays, alongside [[WQHT|HOT 97]]'s [[DJ Enuff]], where she interviewed the biggest names in music such as [[Jay Z]] and [[Mariah Carey]]. She resigned from Hot 97 on June 18, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vibe.com/article/angie-martinez-resigns-hot-97|title=Angie Martinez Resigns From Hot 97|work=Vibe|accessdate=9 March 2015}}</ref> She was announced to have signed on with Hot 97's main New York radio competitor, Power 105.1 ([[WWPR-FM]]) on June 19, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/music-arts/angie-martinez-joins-power-105-resigning-hot-97-article-1.1836068 |title=Angie Martinez joins Power 105.1 after leaving Hot 97 |website=NY Daily News |date=2014-06-19 |accessdate=2016-02-26}}</ref> She truly saw her claim to fame when famous Youtuber Danny Gonzalez made a simple video about her radio station. She works for a very powerful company that owns the radio station so she has a lot of legal on her side.\n\n==Acting==\nAs an actress, Angie received small roles in independent hip hop films such as ''[[Blood is Thicker Than Water]]'' and ''[[Paper Soldiers]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Paper Soldiers|website=IMDb.com|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0309986/fullcredits?ref_=tt_cl_sm#cast|accessdate=2016-02-26}}</ref> She then appeared in ''[[Brown Sugar (2002 film)|Brown Sugar]]''<ref>{{cite web|title=Brown sugar|website=IMDb.com|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0297037/fullcredits?ref_=tt_cl_sm#cast|accessdate=2016-02-26}}</ref> starring [[Taye Diggs]], [[Queen Latifah]] and [[Sanaa Lathan]]. In October 2002, Martinez appeared in [[Paid in Full (2002 film)|''Paid In Full'']].  More recently, she appeared in [[Video Girl (film)|''Video Girl'']] in 2011, ''[[Generation Um...]]'' in 2012, and in the docu-comedy television series ''[[This Is Hot 97]]'' in 2014. Most recently she appear in a Youtube video sky rocketing her to fame. She also has a knack for acting like she was correct and not admitting when she is wrong. Also appeared in \" I pretended to sue Danny Gonzalez.\" (2020)\n\n==Music career==\nIn 1996, Martinez was encouraged to give rapping a shot by friend [[KRS-One]]. She appeared on his track \"Heartbeat\" from his 1997 album ''[[I Got Next]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/KRS-One-Heartbeat-A-Friend/release/496564 |title=KRS-One - Heartbeat / A Friend (Vinyl) |website=Discogs.com |date= |accessdate=2016-02-26}}</ref>  After the song gained a strong fan following, another friend, [[Lil' Kim]], offered her a spot on the \"Ladies Night Remix\" of her song \"[[Not Tonight]]\" for the ''[[Nothing to Lose (1997 film)|Nothing to Lose]]'' soundtrack.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2013/04/the-50-best-rap-songs-by-women/ladies-night-not-tonight-remix |title=Lil Kim f/ Da Brat, Missy Elliott, Angie Martinez, & Left Eye \"Ladies Night (Not Tonight Remix)\" (1997) - The 50 Best Rap Songs by Women |publisher=Complex |date= |accessdate=2016-02-26}}</ref>  Along with [[Missy Elliott]], [[Lisa \"Left Eye\" Lopes]] and [[Da Brat]], the ladies enjoyed one of the most successful singles of 1997. It peaked on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] chart at #6,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/307304/lil-kim/chart |title=Lil' Kim - Chart history |publisher=Billboard |date= |accessdate=2016-02-26}}</ref> and reached #3 on the Hip-Hop / R&B charts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/307304/lil-kim/chart?f=367 |title=Lil' Kim - Chart history |publisher=Billboard |date= |accessdate=2016-02-26}}</ref> The single sold over 1,000,000 copies and was certified Platinum.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?content_selector=gold-platinum-searchable-database# |title=Gold & Platinum |publisher=RIAA |accessdate=2016-02-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140830055854/http://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?content_selector=gold-platinum-searchable-database |archivedate=2014-08-30 }}</ref>  The ladies were nominated for two [[Grammy Awards]] that year, and were also invited to perform the song live on the [[MTV Video Music Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KFJER15v9zg |title=Lil Kim - Ladies Night \"Live\" (Not Tonight Remix 1997) |publisher=YouTube |date=2012-03-23 |accessdate=2016-02-26}}</ref>\n\nA major label battle began to sign Martinez to a recording contract. Her appearance on other rapper's material was in high demand. She recorded songs with [[Mary J. Blige]] (\"Christmas in the City\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lyricsty.com/mary-j-blige-christmas-in-the-city-feat-angie-martinez-lyrics.html |title=Mary J Blige - Christmas In The City (Feat. Angie Martinez) Lyrics |website=Lyricsty.com |date= |accessdate=2016-02-26}}</ref> ), [[Cuban Link]] (\"Freak Out\"), [[N.O.R.E.]] (\"Oh No Remix\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/Noreaga-Oh-No-Remix/release/1663966 |title=Noreaga - Oh No (Remix) (Vinyl) |website=Discogs.com |date= |accessdate=2016-02-26}}</ref> ), [[Beenie Man]] (\"Tell Me Remix\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://genius.com/Beenie-man-tell-me-remix-lyrics |title=Beenie Man \u2013 Tell Me (Remix) Lyrics &#124; Genius |website=genius.com |date= |accessdate=2016-02-26}}</ref> ) and [[Funkmaster Flex]] & [[Big Kap]]'s compilation album ''The Tunnel'' (\"Wow\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rhapsody.com/artist/funkmaster-flex/album/the-tunnel-edited/track/wow---featuring-angie-martinez |title=The Tunnel (Edited) by Funkmaster Flex |publisher=Rhapsody |date=1999-01-01 |accessdate=2016-02-26}}</ref> ). She also recorded interludes for mixtapes by [[Kid Capri]], [[DJ Clue]] and [[DJ Kayslay]]. In 2001, she appeared in the music video for [[Jay-Z]] and [[R. Kelly]]'s \"Guilty Until Proven Innocent\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aCHB4GCyufE |title=JAY-Z - Guilty Until Proven Innocent ft. R. Kelly |publisher=YouTube |date=2009-06-16 |accessdate=2016-02-26}}</ref>\n\nOn April 17, 2001, she finally released her delayed debut album, ''[[Up Close and Personal (Angie Martinez album)|Up Close and Personal]]''.<ref>{{cite web|author=Kerry L. Smith |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/up-close-and-personal-mw0000587240 |title=Up Close and Personal - Angie Martinez &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |date=2001-04-17 |accessdate=2016-02-26}}</ref> The album included production by [[DJ Clue]], [[Salaam Remi]], [[Knobody]] and [[RocWilder]] among others, and featured guest appearances by [[Jay-Z]], [[Snoop Dogg|Snoop Doggy Dogg]], [[Mary J. Blige]], [[Wyclef Jean]], [[Busta Rhymes]] and [[Kool G. Rap]]. The first single, \"Dem Thangzzz\" was produced by [[The Neptunes]], and also featured background vocals by [[Pharrell Williams]] and [[Q-Tip (musician)|Q-Tip]].  The album debuted at #32 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] Albums Chart,<ref name=\"billboard1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/279315/angie-martinez/chart?f=305 |title=Angie Martinez - Chart history |publisher=Billboard |date= |accessdate=2016-02-26}}</ref> and #7 on the Billboard Top R&B/Hip-Hop Album Chart<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/279315/angie-martinez/chart?f=333 |title=Angie Martinez - Chart history |publisher=Billboard |date= |accessdate=2016-02-26}}</ref> selling 69,000 its first week.  The second single, \"Coast 2 Coast\" (Suavamente) featuring rapper [[Wyclef Jean]] re-sparked interest in the album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://voices.yahoo.com/angie-martinez-close-personal-hot-97-djs-debut-101661.html |title=Yahoo |website=Voices.yahoo.com |date=2014-04-23 |accessdate=2016-02-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140729004334/http://voices.yahoo.com/angie-martinez-close-personal-hot-97-djs-debut-101661.html |archivedate=2014-07-29 }}</ref>{{unreliable source?|date=July 2015}}  She promoted the album with magazine posters, in-store signings, club appearances and television appearances with [[MTV]] and [[Black Entertainment Television|BET]].\n\nFollowing her first album's release, Angie began work on a second record, 2002's ''[[Animal House (Angie Martinez album)|Animal House]]''. In order to build anticipation for the record, she appeared on BET's ''[[Rap City (BET program)|Rap City]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7kaNVJ74z18 |title=Sacario & Angie Martinez BET Rap City The Basement. Classic Episode!!! |publisher=YouTube |date=2010-03-15 |accessdate=2016-02-26}}</ref>  and began a nationwide radio tour. She recorded a verse for the remix to her artist [[Sacario]] record \"Live Big\". It became the number one record in the tri-state area and coincidentally coincided with the release of Martinez's first single from her second album, \"[[If I Could Go (Song)|If I Could Go]]\" which also featured [[Sacario]] and singer [[Lil' Mo]]. \"If I Could Go\" became a huge crossover hit on pop radio, climbing into the top 20 on The Billboard Hot 100 Chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/279315/angie-martinez/chart |title=Angie Martinez - Chart history |publisher=Billboard |date= |accessdate=2016-02-26}}</ref>  It became the #1 played on urban radio in 2002. The album, ''[[Animal House (Angie Martinez album)|Animal House]]'' (named after Martinez's own production company and recording posse), was released on August 21, 2002. It entered the Billboard Hot 200 Albums Chart at #11,<ref name=\"billboard1\"/> and the Billboard Hot Hip-Hop / R&B Charts selling 92,000 units in its first week. The follow-up single, \"Take You Home\" featuring R&B singer [[Kelis]] became a minor hit reaching the top 100 on the Billboard Hot 100.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/279315/angie-martinez/chart?f=379 |title=Angie Martinez - Chart history |publisher=Billboard |date= |accessdate=2016-02-26}}</ref> The album was more strongly received by critics and fans. Following the release of the album, she was featured on a remix for labelmate Lil' Mo's track \"Gangster\", and [[Nina Sky]]'s hype single \"Time to Go\". Following this she announced she was retiring from the recording industry to concentrate on her other projects.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sohh.com/2012/08/angie_martinez_on_shelving_rap_career_i.html |title=Angie Martinez On Shelving Rap Career: \"I Cringe Sometimes When I Hear Some Of Those Songs\" \u2013 For The Best In Hip-Hop News |website=SOHH.com |date=2015-12-09 |accessdate=2016-02-26}}</ref>\n\nIn 2002, Martinez was hired to be a judge on the [[American Idol (season 2)|second season of ''American Idol'']], but quit after a few days of auditions, citing discomfort with crushing the dreams of auditioners.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1458450/martinez-quits-american-idol.jhtml |title=Angie Martinez Quits 'American Idol' After Two Episodes |publisher=MTV |date=2002-10-31 |accessdate=2016-02-26}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2014, Martinez was signed to Jay-Z's [[Roc Nation]].\n\n==Personal life==\nMartinez's father was [[Puerto Ricans|Puerto Rican]] and her mother was of [[Cubans|Cuban]] and [[Dominican Republic|Dominican]] descent. She has a son born in 2003 with [[Nokio|Tamir \"Nokio\" Ruffin]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.contactmusic.com/new/xmlfeed.nsf/mndwebpages/angie%20martinez%20gives%20birth|title=Angie Martinez Gives Birth|website=Contactmusic.com|accessdate=9 March 2015}}</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20071225065207/http://experts.about.com/e/a/an/Angie_Martinez.htm] {{dead link|date=January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.undercover.com.au/news/2003/20030822_druhill.html |title=Undercover |website=Undercover.com.au |accessdate=2016-02-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070521040320/http://www.undercover.com.au/news/2003/20030822_druhill.html |archivedate=2007-05-21 }}</ref> of [[Dru Hill]].\n\nIn 2014, Martinez supported [[CC Sabathia]]'s charity, the PitCCh In Foundation, by running in the 2014 [[New York City Marathon]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/blogs/yankees/cc-sabathia-wife-amber-gears-nyc-marathon-blog-entry-1.1989145 |title=CC Sabathia's wife Amber gears up for NYC Marathon |website=NY Daily News |date=2014-10-27 |accessdate=2016-02-26}}</ref> and has no friends because she has been protected for too long by legal \n\n==Awards and nominations==\n*[[NAB Marconi Radio Awards]]\n**2018, Major Market Personality of the Year<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://radioink.com/2018/09/28/here-are-the-2018-marconi-award-winners/|title=Here Are The 2018 Marconi Award Winners - Radio Ink|date=2018-09-28|work=Radio Ink|access-date=2018-09-28|language=en-US}}</ref>\n*[[BET Awards]]\n** 2002, Best Female Hip-Hop Artist (Nominated)\n* [[Grammy Awards]]\n** 1998, Best Rap Performance by a Duo or Group \"Not Tonight\" (Nominated)\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Studio albums===\n{|class=\"wikitable\" \n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"|Year\n! rowspan=\"2\"|Album \n! colspan=\"2\"|Peak chart positions\n|- \n!style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%\"|[[Billboard 200|U.S.]]\n!style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%\"|[[Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums|U.S. R&B]]\n|-\n|2001\n|'''''[[Up Close and Personal (Angie Martinez album)|Up Close and Personal]]'''''\n*<small>Released: April 17, 2001\n*Label: [[Elektra Records|Elektra]]\n*Format: [[Compact Disc|CD]], [[Music download|digital download]]</small>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|32\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|7\n|- \n|2002\n|'''''[[Animal House (Angie Martinez album)|Animal House]]'''''\n*<small>Released: August 20, 2002\n*Label: Elektra\n*Format: [[Compact Disc|CD]], [[Music download|digital download]]</small>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|11\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|6\n|}\n\n==Singles==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!scope=\"col\" rowspan=2|Year\n!scope=\"col\" rowspan=2 style=\"width:24em;\"|Song\n!scope=\"col\" colspan=4|Peak chart positions<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/up-close-and-personal-r527525/charts-awards/billboard-single|title=Up Close and Personal - Angie Martinez - Awards - AllMusic|work=AllMusic|accessdate=9 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/animal-house-r599408/charts-awards/billboard-single|title=Animal House - Angie Martinez - Awards - AllMusic|work=AllMusic|accessdate=9 March 2015}}</ref>\n!scope=\"col\" rowspan=2|Album\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:4em;font-size:90%;\"|[[Billboard Top 100|US]]\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:4em;font-size:90%;\"|[[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs|U.S. R&B]]\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:4em;font-size:90%;\"|[[Hot Rap Tracks|U.S. Rap]]\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:4em;font-size:90%;\"|[[UK Singles Chart|UK]]\n|-\n||2000\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|\"Mi Amor\" <small>(featuring [[Jay-Z]])</small>\n| \u2014\n| 51\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|rowspan=3|''Up Close and Personal''\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2001\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|\"Dem Thangs\"\n| \u2014\n| 80\n| 24\n| \u2014\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|\"Coast 2 Coast\"\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|-\n||2002\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|\"[[If I Could Go!|If I Could Go]]\" <small>(featuring [[Lil' Mo]] & Sacario)</small>\n| 15\n| 26\n| 11\n| 61\n|rowspan=2|''Animal House''\n|-\n||2003\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|\"Take You Home\" <small>(featuring [[Kelis]])</small>\n| 85\n| 62\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|-\n| colspan=\"7\" style=\"font-size:90%\"| \"\u2014\" denotes a title that did not chart, or was not released in that territory.\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Mami (hip hop)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080807055141/http://www.theangiemartinezshow.com/ Angie Martinez's Official Website]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/user/AngieMartinez97 Angie Martinez on YouTube]\n* [http://www.hot97.com/angiemartinez Angie Martinez's page at Hot97.com]\n* [http://www.hot97.com Hot97.com]\n* {{IMDb name | id=0553460 | name=Angie Martinez}}\n\n{{Roc Nation}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Martinez, Angie}}\n[[Category:1971 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Actresses from New York City]]\n[[Category:American female models]]\n[[Category:American female singers]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American actresses of Puerto Rican descent]]\n[[Category:American radio personalities]]\n[[Category:American female rappers]]\n[[Category:Elektra Records artists]]\n[[Category:Hispanic and Latino American rappers]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:People from the Bronx]]\n[[Category:Rappers from Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:John Dewey High School alumni]]\n[[Category:Cuban female rappers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American rappers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American women musicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{BLP sources|date=March 2011}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name = Angie Martinez\n| alias = The Voice of New York\n| background = solo_singer\n| birth_name = Angela Martinez\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|mf=yes|1971|1|9}}\n| birth_place =[[Brooklyn, New York|Brooklyn]], [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|New York]], U. S.\n| genre = [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n| occupation = [[Radio personality]], \n| years_active = 1992\u2013present\n| label = [[Elektra Records]], [[Roc Nation]]\n| website = [http://www.theangiemartinezshow.com/ TheAngieMartinezShow.com]\n}}\n\n'''Angela Martinez''' (born January 9, 1971) is an [[United States|American]] radio personality, rapper, and actress of Puerto Rican, Cuban and Dominican heritage.<ref>[https://www.amny.com/news/hispanic-heritage-month-7-nyc-power-players-1.9485464] {{dead link|date=January 2020}}</ref> Nicknamed \u201cThe Voice of New York\u201d, her afternoon radio show has consistently been ranked #1 with more young listeners than any other radio program in the country.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.latintrends.com/happy-birthday-angie-martinez/ |title=Happy Birthday, Angie Martinez! |website=Latintrends.com |date=2012-01-09 |accessdate=2016-02-26}}</ref>\n\n==Radio career==\nAngie Martinez got her first break in radio at the age of 16 answering hot lines at the urban radio station [[WQHT]] (\"Hot 97\"). There she met popular DJ [[Funkmaster Flex]], and began working as his prot\u00e9g\u00e9. Martinez quickly picked up on the craft of running a successful radio program. She hosted the Afternoon Drive weekdays, alongside [[WQHT|HOT 97]]'s [[DJ Enuff]], where she interviewed the biggest names in music such as [[Jay Z]] and [[Mariah Carey]]. She resigned from Hot 97 on June 18, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vibe.com/article/angie-martinez-resigns-hot-97|title=Angie Martinez Resigns From Hot 97|work=Vibe|accessdate=9 March 2015}}</ref> She was announced to have signed on with Hot 97's main New York radio competitor, Power 105.1 ([[WWPR-FM]]) on June 19, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/music-arts/angie-martinez-joins-power-105-resigning-hot-97-article-1.1836068 |title=Angie Martinez joins Power 105.1 after leaving Hot 97 |website=NY Daily News |date=2014-06-19 |accessdate=2016-02-26}}</ref>\n\n==Acting==\nAs an actress, Angie received small roles in independent hip hop films such as ''[[Blood is Thicker Than Water]]'' and ''[[Paper Soldiers]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Paper Soldiers|website=IMDb.com|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0309986/fullcredits?ref_=tt_cl_sm#cast|accessdate=2016-02-26}}</ref> She then appeared in ''[[Brown Sugar (2002 film)|Brown Sugar]]''<ref>{{cite web|title=Brown sugar|website=IMDb.com|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0297037/fullcredits?ref_=tt_cl_sm#cast|accessdate=2016-02-26}}</ref> starring [[Taye Diggs]], [[Queen Latifah]] and [[Sanaa Lathan]]. In October 2002, Martinez appeared in [[Paid in Full (2002 film)|''Paid In Full'']].  More recently, she appeared in [[Video Girl (film)|''Video Girl'']] in 2011, ''[[Generation Um...]]'' in 2012, and in the docu-comedy television series ''[[This Is Hot 97]]'' in 2014.\n\n==Music career==\nIn 1996, Martinez was encouraged to give rapping a shot by friend [[KRS-One]]. She appeared on his track \"Heartbeat\" from his 1997 album ''[[I Got Next]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/KRS-One-Heartbeat-A-Friend/release/496564 |title=KRS-One - Heartbeat / A Friend (Vinyl) |website=Discogs.com |date= |accessdate=2016-02-26}}</ref>  After the song gained a strong fan following, another friend, [[Lil' Kim]], offered her a spot on the \"Ladies Night Remix\" of her song \"[[Not Tonight]]\" for the ''[[Nothing to Lose (1997 film)|Nothing to Lose]]'' soundtrack.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.complex.com/music/2013/04/the-50-best-rap-songs-by-women/ladies-night-not-tonight-remix |title=Lil Kim f/ Da Brat, Missy Elliott, Angie Martinez, & Left Eye \"Ladies Night (Not Tonight Remix)\" (1997) - The 50 Best Rap Songs by Women |publisher=Complex |date= |accessdate=2016-02-26}}</ref>  Along with [[Missy Elliott]], [[Lisa \"Left Eye\" Lopes]] and [[Da Brat]], the ladies enjoyed one of the most successful singles of 1997. It peaked on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] chart at #6,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/307304/lil-kim/chart |title=Lil' Kim - Chart history |publisher=Billboard |date= |accessdate=2016-02-26}}</ref> and reached #3 on the Hip-Hop / R&B charts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/307304/lil-kim/chart?f=367 |title=Lil' Kim - Chart history |publisher=Billboard |date= |accessdate=2016-02-26}}</ref> The single sold over 1,000,000 copies and was certified Platinum.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?content_selector=gold-platinum-searchable-database# |title=Gold & Platinum |publisher=RIAA |accessdate=2016-02-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140830055854/http://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?content_selector=gold-platinum-searchable-database |archivedate=2014-08-30 }}</ref>  The ladies were nominated for two [[Grammy Awards]] that year, and were also invited to perform the song live on the [[MTV Video Music Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KFJER15v9zg |title=Lil Kim - Ladies Night \"Live\" (Not Tonight Remix 1997) |publisher=YouTube |date=2012-03-23 |accessdate=2016-02-26}}</ref>\n\nA major label battle began to sign Martinez to a recording contract. Her appearance on other rapper's material was in high demand. She recorded songs with [[Mary J. Blige]] (\"Christmas in the City\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lyricsty.com/mary-j-blige-christmas-in-the-city-feat-angie-martinez-lyrics.html |title=Mary J Blige - Christmas In The City (Feat. Angie Martinez) Lyrics |website=Lyricsty.com |date= |accessdate=2016-02-26}}</ref> ), [[Cuban Link]] (\"Freak Out\"), [[N.O.R.E.]] (\"Oh No Remix\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.discogs.com/Noreaga-Oh-No-Remix/release/1663966 |title=Noreaga - Oh No (Remix) (Vinyl) |website=Discogs.com |date= |accessdate=2016-02-26}}</ref> ), [[Beenie Man]] (\"Tell Me Remix\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://genius.com/Beenie-man-tell-me-remix-lyrics |title=Beenie Man \u2013 Tell Me (Remix) Lyrics &#124; Genius |website=genius.com |date= |accessdate=2016-02-26}}</ref> ) and [[Funkmaster Flex]] & [[Big Kap]]'s compilation album ''The Tunnel'' (\"Wow\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rhapsody.com/artist/funkmaster-flex/album/the-tunnel-edited/track/wow---featuring-angie-martinez |title=The Tunnel (Edited) by Funkmaster Flex |publisher=Rhapsody |date=1999-01-01 |accessdate=2016-02-26}}</ref> ). She also recorded interludes for mixtapes by [[Kid Capri]], [[DJ Clue]] and [[DJ Kayslay]]. In 2001, she appeared in the music video for [[Jay-Z]] and [[R. Kelly]]'s \"Guilty Until Proven Innocent\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aCHB4GCyufE |title=JAY-Z - Guilty Until Proven Innocent ft. R. Kelly |publisher=YouTube |date=2009-06-16 |accessdate=2016-02-26}}</ref>\n\nOn April 17, 2001, she finally released her delayed debut album, ''[[Up Close and Personal (Angie Martinez album)|Up Close and Personal]]''.<ref>{{cite web|author=Kerry L. Smith |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/up-close-and-personal-mw0000587240 |title=Up Close and Personal - Angie Martinez &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |date=2001-04-17 |accessdate=2016-02-26}}</ref> The album included production by [[DJ Clue]], [[Salaam Remi]], [[Knobody]] and [[RocWilder]] among others, and featured guest appearances by [[Jay-Z]], [[Snoop Dogg|Snoop Doggy Dogg]], [[Mary J. Blige]], [[Wyclef Jean]], [[Busta Rhymes]] and [[Kool G. Rap]]. The first single, \"Dem Thangzzz\" was produced by [[The Neptunes]], and also featured background vocals by [[Pharrell Williams]] and [[Q-Tip (musician)|Q-Tip]].  The album debuted at #32 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] Albums Chart,<ref name=\"billboard1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/279315/angie-martinez/chart?f=305 |title=Angie Martinez - Chart history |publisher=Billboard |date= |accessdate=2016-02-26}}</ref> and #7 on the Billboard Top R&B/Hip-Hop Album Chart<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/279315/angie-martinez/chart?f=333 |title=Angie Martinez - Chart history |publisher=Billboard |date= |accessdate=2016-02-26}}</ref> selling 69,000 its first week.  The second single, \"Coast 2 Coast\" (Suavamente) featuring rapper [[Wyclef Jean]] re-sparked interest in the album.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://voices.yahoo.com/angie-martinez-close-personal-hot-97-djs-debut-101661.html |title=Yahoo |website=Voices.yahoo.com |date=2014-04-23 |accessdate=2016-02-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140729004334/http://voices.yahoo.com/angie-martinez-close-personal-hot-97-djs-debut-101661.html |archivedate=2014-07-29 }}</ref>{{unreliable source?|date=July 2015}}  She promoted the album with magazine posters, in-store signings, club appearances and television appearances with [[MTV]] and [[Black Entertainment Television|BET]].\n\nFollowing her first album's release, Angie began work on a second record, 2002's ''[[Animal House (Angie Martinez album)|Animal House]]''. In order to build anticipation for the record, she appeared on BET's ''[[Rap City (BET program)|Rap City]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7kaNVJ74z18 |title=Sacario & Angie Martinez BET Rap City The Basement. Classic Episode!!! |publisher=YouTube |date=2010-03-15 |accessdate=2016-02-26}}</ref>  and began a nationwide radio tour. She recorded a verse for the remix to her artist [[Sacario]] record \"Live Big\". It became the number one record in the tri-state area and coincidentally coincided with the release of Martinez's first single from her second album, \"[[If I Could Go (Song)|If I Could Go]]\" which also featured [[Sacario]] and singer [[Lil' Mo]]. \"If I Could Go\" became a huge crossover hit on pop radio, climbing into the top 20 on The Billboard Hot 100 Chart.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/279315/angie-martinez/chart |title=Angie Martinez - Chart history |publisher=Billboard |date= |accessdate=2016-02-26}}</ref>  It became the #1 played on urban radio in 2002. The album, ''[[Animal House (Angie Martinez album)|Animal House]]'' (named after Martinez's own production company and recording posse), was released on August 21, 2002. It entered the Billboard Hot 200 Albums Chart at #11,<ref name=\"billboard1\"/> and the Billboard Hot Hip-Hop / R&B Charts selling 92,000 units in its first week. The follow-up single, \"Take You Home\" featuring R&B singer [[Kelis]] became a minor hit reaching the top 100 on the Billboard Hot 100.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/279315/angie-martinez/chart?f=379 |title=Angie Martinez - Chart history |publisher=Billboard |date= |accessdate=2016-02-26}}</ref> The album was more strongly received by critics and fans. Following the release of the album, she was featured on a remix for labelmate Lil' Mo's track \"Gangster\", and [[Nina Sky]]'s hype single \"Time to Go\". Following this she announced she was retiring from the recording industry to concentrate on her other projects.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sohh.com/2012/08/angie_martinez_on_shelving_rap_career_i.html |title=Angie Martinez On Shelving Rap Career: \"I Cringe Sometimes When I Hear Some Of Those Songs\" \u2013 For The Best In Hip-Hop News |website=SOHH.com |date=2015-12-09 |accessdate=2016-02-26}}</ref>\n\nIn 2002, Martinez was hired to be a judge on the [[American Idol (season 2)|second season of ''American Idol'']], but quit after a few days of auditions, citing discomfort with crushing the dreams of auditioners.<ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1458450/martinez-quits-american-idol.jhtml |title=Angie Martinez Quits 'American Idol' After Two Episodes |publisher=MTV |date=2002-10-31 |accessdate=2016-02-26}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2014, Martinez was signed to Jay-Z's [[Roc Nation]].\n\n==Personal life==\nMartinez's father was [[Puerto Ricans|Puerto Rican]] and her mother was of [[Cubans|Cuban]] and [[Dominican Republic|Dominican]] descent. She has a son born in 2003 with [[Nokio|Tamir \"Nokio\" Ruffin]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.contactmusic.com/new/xmlfeed.nsf/mndwebpages/angie%20martinez%20gives%20birth|title=Angie Martinez Gives Birth|website=Contactmusic.com|accessdate=9 March 2015}}</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20071225065207/http://experts.about.com/e/a/an/Angie_Martinez.htm] {{dead link|date=January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.undercover.com.au/news/2003/20030822_druhill.html |title=Undercover |website=Undercover.com.au |accessdate=2016-02-26 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070521040320/http://www.undercover.com.au/news/2003/20030822_druhill.html |archivedate=2007-05-21 }}</ref> of [[Dru Hill]].\n\nIn 2014, Martinez supported [[CC Sabathia]]'s charity, the PitCCh In Foundation, by running in the 2014 [[New York City Marathon]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/blogs/yankees/cc-sabathia-wife-amber-gears-nyc-marathon-blog-entry-1.1989145 |title=CC Sabathia's wife Amber gears up for NYC Marathon |website=NY Daily News |date=2014-10-27 |accessdate=2016-02-26}}</ref>\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n*[[NAB Marconi Radio Awards]]\n**2018, Major Market Personality of the Year<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://radioink.com/2018/09/28/here-are-the-2018-marconi-award-winners/|title=Here Are The 2018 Marconi Award Winners - Radio Ink|date=2018-09-28|work=Radio Ink|access-date=2018-09-28|language=en-US}}</ref>\n*[[BET Awards]]\n** 2002, Best Female Hip-Hop Artist (Nominated)\n* [[Grammy Awards]]\n** 1998, Best Rap Performance by a Duo or Group \"Not Tonight\" (Nominated)\n\n==Discography==\n\n===Studio albums===\n{|class=\"wikitable\" \n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"|Year\n! rowspan=\"2\"|Album \n! colspan=\"2\"|Peak chart positions\n|- \n!style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%\"|[[Billboard 200|U.S.]]\n!style=\"width:3em;font-size:85%\"|[[Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums|U.S. R&B]]\n|-\n|2001\n|'''''[[Up Close and Personal (Angie Martinez album)|Up Close and Personal]]'''''\n*<small>Released: April 17, 2001\n*Label: [[Elektra Records|Elektra]]\n*Format: [[Compact Disc|CD]], [[Music download|digital download]]</small>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|32\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|7\n|- \n|2002\n|'''''[[Animal House (Angie Martinez album)|Animal House]]'''''\n*<small>Released: August 20, 2002\n*Label: Elektra\n*Format: [[Compact Disc|CD]], [[Music download|digital download]]</small>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|11\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|6\n|}\n\n==Singles==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n!scope=\"col\" rowspan=2|Year\n!scope=\"col\" rowspan=2 style=\"width:24em;\"|Song\n!scope=\"col\" colspan=4|Peak chart positions<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/up-close-and-personal-r527525/charts-awards/billboard-single|title=Up Close and Personal - Angie Martinez - Awards - AllMusic|work=AllMusic|accessdate=9 March 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/animal-house-r599408/charts-awards/billboard-single|title=Animal House - Angie Martinez - Awards - AllMusic|work=AllMusic|accessdate=9 March 2015}}</ref>\n!scope=\"col\" rowspan=2|Album\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:4em;font-size:90%;\"|[[Billboard Top 100|US]]\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:4em;font-size:90%;\"|[[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs|U.S. R&B]]\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:4em;font-size:90%;\"|[[Hot Rap Tracks|U.S. Rap]]\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:4em;font-size:90%;\"|[[UK Singles Chart|UK]]\n|-\n||2000\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|\"Mi Amor\" <small>(featuring [[Jay-Z]])</small>\n| \u2014\n| 51\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|rowspan=3|''Up Close and Personal''\n|-\n|rowspan=2|2001\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|\"Dem Thangs\"\n| \u2014\n| 80\n| 24\n| \u2014\n|-\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|\"Coast 2 Coast\"\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|-\n||2002\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|\"[[If I Could Go!|If I Could Go]]\" <small>(featuring [[Lil' Mo]] & Sacario)</small>\n| 15\n| 26\n| 11\n| 61\n|rowspan=2|''Animal House''\n|-\n||2003\n|style=\"text-align:left;\"|\"Take You Home\" <small>(featuring [[Kelis]])</small>\n| 85\n| 62\n| \u2014\n| \u2014\n|-\n| colspan=\"7\" style=\"font-size:90%\"| \"\u2014\" denotes a title that did not chart, or was not released in that territory.\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Mami (hip hop)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080807055141/http://www.theangiemartinezshow.com/ Angie Martinez's Official Website]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/user/AngieMartinez97 Angie Martinez on YouTube]\n* [http://www.hot97.com/angiemartinez Angie Martinez's page at Hot97.com]\n* [http://www.hot97.com Hot97.com]\n* {{IMDb name | id=0553460 | name=Angie Martinez}}\n\n{{Roc Nation}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Martinez, Angie}}\n[[Category:1971 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Actresses from New York City]]\n[[Category:American female models]]\n[[Category:American female singers]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American actresses of Puerto Rican descent]]\n[[Category:American radio personalities]]\n[[Category:American female rappers]]\n[[Category:Elektra Records artists]]\n[[Category:Hispanic and Latino American rappers]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Brooklyn]]\n[[Category:People from the Bronx]