{"title_page": "Prince Richard, Duke of Gloucester", "text_new": "{{about|the current Duke of Gloucester|the King previously known as Prince Richard, Duke of Gloucester|Richard III of England}}\n{{short description|Youngest grandchild of King George V and Queen Mary}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox royalty\n| name         = Prince Richard\n| title        = [[Duke of Gloucester]] ([[#Titles, styles, honours and Arms|more]])\n| image        = The Duke of Gloucester (cropped).jpg\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1944|8|26|df=yes}}\n| birth_place  = St. Matthew's Hospital, [[Northampton]], England<ref name=Birth/>\n| full name    = Richard Alexander Walter George<ref name=\"sur\">As a titled royal, Richard needs no surname, but, when one is used, it is [[House of Windsor|Windsor]].</ref>\n| house        = [[House of Windsor|Windsor]]\n| suc-type     = Heir apparent\n| spouse       = {{marriage|[[Birgitte van Deurs]]|8 July 1972}}\n| issue        = {{plainlist|\n* [[Alexander Windsor, Earl of Ulster]]\n* [[Lady Davina Windsor]]\n* Lady Rose Gilman\n}}\n| father       = [[Prince Henry, Duke of Gloucester]]\n| mother       = [[Lady Alice Montagu Douglas Scott]]\n}}\n\n{{British Royal Family}}\n\n'''Prince Richard, Duke of Gloucester''', {{post-nominals|country=GBR|sep=,|size=100%|KG|GCVO|GCStJ}} (Richard Alexander Walter George; born 26 August 1944) is the youngest [[Descendants of George V and Mary of Teck|grandchild]] of [[King George V]] and [[Mary of Teck|Queen Mary]]. He practised as an architect until the death of his [[Prince William of Gloucester|elder brother]] placed him in direct line to inherit his [[Prince Henry, Duke of Gloucester|father]]'s [[dukedom of Gloucester]], which he inherited, as the second duke, in 1974. He is a paternal cousin of Queen [[Elizabeth II]], and currently 27th in the [[line of succession to the British throne]] as well as the first in line not descended from [[King George VI]].\n\n==Early life==\nPrince Richard was born on 26 August 1944 at 2:15 pm afternoon at St. Matthew\u2019s Hospital in [[Northampton]], He was first royal member to be born at medical building of United Kongdom<ref name=Birth>{{London Gazette |issue= 36678 |date= 29 August 1944 |page=4017 }}</ref> His father was [[Prince Henry, Duke of Gloucester]], the third son of [[George V]] and [[Mary of Teck|Queen Mary]]. His mother was [[Princess Alice, Duchess of Gloucester]] (''n\u00e9e'' Lady Alice Montagu Douglas Scott), a daughter of the [[John Montagu-Douglas-Scott, 7th Duke of Buccleuch|7th Duke of Buccleuch]] and Lady Margaret Bridgeman. He was baptised at the [[Royal Chapel of All Saints]] in [[Windsor Great Park]] on 20 October 1944 by the retired [[Archbishop of Canterbury]], [[Cosmo Gordon Lang]].{{refn|His godparents were his paternal aunt, [[Queen Elizabeth The Queen Mother|Queen Elizabeth]], [[Princess Marie Louise of Schleswig-Holstein|Princess Marie Louise]] (his cousin), the [[Princess Alice, Countess of Athlone|Countess of Athlone]] (his cousin, for whom her daughter, [[Lady May Abel Smith]] stood [[proxy marriage|proxy]]), the [[Walter Montagu Douglas Scott, 8th Duke of Buccleuch|Duke of Buccleuch]] (his maternal uncle), the [[George Cambridge, 2nd Marquess of Cambridge|Marquess of Cambridge]] (his cousin), Lady Sybil Phipps (his maternal aunt), and [[Harold Alexander, 1st Earl Alexander of Tunis|General the Earl Alexander of Tunis]] (for whom his wife, then [[Margaret Alexander, Countess Alexander of Tunis|Lady Margaret Alexander]], stood proxy). Because of the War, newspapers did not identify the precise location of the christening, saying only that it took place at \"a private chapel in the country\".<ref name=\"times-1944\">[[The Times]], 21 October 1944</ref><ref name=\"times-1942\">[[The Times]], 5 August 1942</ref><ref name=\"Yvonne\">{{cite web|url=http://users.uniserve.com/~canyon/christenings.htm#Christenings |title=Yvonne's Royalty Home Page \u2013 Royal Christenings |publisher=users.uniserve.com |accessdate=30 April 2011}}</ref>}} When Richard was four months old, he accompanied his parents to [[Australia]], where his father served as [[Governor-General of Australia|Governor-General]] from 1945 to 1947. The family returned to [[Barnwell Manor]] in 1947, where Richard was largely raised.\n\nAt the time of his birth, he was fifth in the [[Succession to the British throne|line of succession to the throne]] and second in line to his father's [[duke]]dom, behind his brother, [[Prince William of Gloucester]]. He is 27th in line to the throne {{as of|2019|05|lc=y}}. William died in 1972 when the plane he was piloting crashed at Halfpenny Green near Wolverhampton. Richard then became heir apparent to his father's dukedom and inherited it two years later on the death of the first duke.\n\n== Education and career ==\n[[File:HRH The Duke of Gloucester Allan Warren.jpg|thumb|The Duke in 1989, by [[Allan Warren]]]]\n\nPrince Richard's early education took place at home, under the instruction of Rosamund Ramirez, who had also tutored young King [[Faisal II of Iraq]]; later, he attended [[Wellesley House School]] at [[Broadstairs]] and [[Eton College]].<ref name=\"Bio-Charity\"/> In 1963, he matriculated at [[Magdalene College, Cambridge]] where he read Architecture,<ref name=\"Bio-Charity\"/> graduating with the degree of [[Bachelor of Arts]] in June 1966; he [[proceed]]ed as [[Master of Arts (Oxbridge and Dublin)|MA (Cantab)]] in 1971.\n\nLater in 1966, straight after university, Prince Richard joined the Offices Development Group in the [[Ministry of Works (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Public Building and Works]] for a year of practical work. He returned to [[University of Cambridge|Cambridge]] in 1967, completing both parts of the [[Master's degree|Diploma in Architecture]] degree in June 1969. Upon passing his exams, he became a practising partner in Hunt Thompson Associates in London, an architectural firm.<ref name=\"worcester\">{{cite web|url=http://www.worcester.ac.uk/discover/hrh-prince-richard-the-duke-of-gloucester.html|title=HRH Prince Richard The Duke of Gloucester|year=2008|publisher=University of Worcester|accessdate=21 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nRichard intended to practise full-time as an [[architect]], but took on other responsibilities in 1972, after the death of his elder brother [[Prince William of Gloucester|Prince William]], who crashed his plane in a flying competition. Richard became [[heir apparent]] to his father's dukedom and had to take on additional family obligations and royal duties. He resigned his partnership and began representing his cousin, Elizabeth II, on royal duties.\n\nOn 10 June 1974, Prince Richard succeeded to his father's titles as ''[[Duke of Gloucester]], [[Earl of Ulster]], and [[Baron Culloden]]''. He was elected as a corporate member of the [[Royal Institute of British Architects]] (and FRIBA) in 1972. He is President of the Society of Architect Artists.<ref name=\"worcester\"/> He serves as a Commissioner of the Historic Building and Monuments Commission for England ([[English Heritage]]).\n\nThe Duke has been Patron of construction charity Construction Youth Trust<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.constructionyouth.org.uk/about-us/about-trust/construction-youth-trust-patron|title=Our Patron|publisher=Construction Youth Trust|accessdate=26 September 2016}}</ref> for many years. With his background in architecture, the Duke of Gloucester takes interest in the work of the Trust and frequently visits their projects, in addition to giving his name to their long standing Duke of Gloucester Young Achiever's Scheme Awards. The Duke is also patron of the Architects Benevolent Society.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.architectsjournal.co.uk/home/royal-patron-for-abs/142505.article|title=Royal Patron for ABS|date=6 March 2003|publisher=Architects Journal|last=|first=|website=www.architectsjournal.co.uk|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=24 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nHe is Royal Patron of the UK branch of the charity [[Habitat for Humanity]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.habitatforhumanity.org.uk/blog/2015/10/royal-patron-visits-hfh-hale-county/|publisher=Habitat for Humanity GB|title=Royal Patron visits HFH Hale County|accessdate=12 July 2016|date=30 October 2015}}</ref> Royal Patron of the St George's Society of New York,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stgeorgessociety.org/board.html|title=Board of Directors|publisher=St. George's Society of New York|accessdate=12 July 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130413150308/https://www.stgeorgessociety.org/board.html|archivedate=24 March 2018}}</ref> and President of [[London Society (organisation)|The London Society]].\n\nA keen motorist, Prince Richard passed the [[Advanced Driving Test]] of the [[Institute of Advanced Motorists]], of which he was president for more than 32 years. On his appointment in 1971,<ref name=Motor197110>{{cite magazine | authorlink = Charles Bulmer (Ed) |title = Appointments Register|magazine=Motor| page =57| date = 9 October 1971}}</ref> it was recorded that the new President was \"currently [driving] an [[BMC ADO16|Austin 1300]]\", reflecting the modest image with which he has always been identified. He stood down as President in January 2005.<ref name=\"resignation\">[http://www.iam.org.uk/Pressroom/News_Releases/2005/nr0501.pdf Resignation Press Release] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050517124347/http://www.iam.org.uk/Pressroom/News_Releases/2005/nr0501.pdf |date=17 May 2005 }}</ref>\n\nOn 10 April 2008, the Duke was installed as Founding Chancellor of the [[University of Worcester]] in a ceremony at Worcester Cathedral. A former teacher training college, the institution was raised to university status in 2006.<ref name=\"worcester\"/>\n\n==Marriage and family==\n[[File:Duke and Duchess of Glocstrer.jpg|thumb|right|The Duke and Duchess of Gloucester]]\nOn 8 July 1972, Prince Richard married the [[Denmark|Danish]]-born [[Birgitte van Deurs]] in St Andrew's Church at [[Barnwell, Northamptonshire|Barnwell]], [[Northamptonshire]]; they have three children:\n\n*[[Alexander Windsor, Earl of Ulster]], born 24 October 1974 at [[St Mary's Hospital, London]]. He married [[Claire Booth]] in 2002. The couple have two children.\n*[[Lady Davina Windsor]], born 19 November 1977 at [[St Mary's Hospital, London]]. She married Gary Lewis in 2004. They divorced in 2018. They have two children.\n*Lady Rose Gilman, born 1 March 1980 at [[St Mary's Hospital, London]]. She married George Gilman in 2008. The couple have two children.\nThe Duke and Duchess of Gloucester's official residence is at [[Kensington Palace]] in London.<ref>{{cite web|title=Royal residences: Kensington Palace |url=http://www.royal.gov.uk/TheRoyalResidences/KensingtonPalace/Today.aspx |publisher=Official website of the Royal Family |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130726232558/http://www.royal.gov.uk/TheRoyalResidences/KensingtonPalace/Today.aspx |archivedate=26 July 2013 }}</ref> They have leased their private home, [[Barnwell Manor]], since 1994.\n\n==Activities==\n\nThe Duke of Gloucester, accompanied by the Duchess, represented his cousin [[Elizabeth II]] at the [[Solomon Islands]] independence celebrations on 7 July 1978.<ref>[http://www.solomonencyclopaedia.net/biogs/E000475b.htm Gloucester, Duke and Duchess of], Solomon Islands Historical Encyclopaedia 1893-1978, Retrieved 2019-02-06.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.solomontimes.com/news/solomon-islands-to-get-a-royal-visit/1954 |title=Solomon Islands to Get a Royal Visit' |publisher=Solomon Islands Times |date=17 June 2008 |accessdate=6 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 April 2008, the Duke of Gloucester was officially installed as inaugural [[Chancellor (education)|Chancellor]] of the [[University of Worcester]] at a ceremony in [[Worcester Cathedral]]. In this role, the [[Prince]] officiates at degree ceremonies and major events, as well as promoting the University overseas.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.worc.ac.uk/discover/hrh-prince-richard-the-duke-of-gloucester.html|title=HRH Prince Richard The Duke of Gloucester|publisher=University of Worcester|accessdate=25 May 2018}}</ref> The Duke carried out the first of these duties on 5 and 6 November 2008 at the Graduation Award Ceremonies.\n\nThe Duke is also patron of the [[Severn Valley Railway]] and the [[Pestalozzi International Village|Pestalozzi International Village Trust]]. He is also a patron of the [[British Homeopathic Association]], a charity dedicated to the study, research and promotion of [[homeopathy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.britishhomeopathic.org/charity/bha-events/reception-with-the-duke-of-gloucester/|title=Royal support for homeopathy|publisher=British Homeopathic Association|accessdate=25 May 2018|date=March 2016}}</ref> He shares a name with another Duke of Gloucester, [[Richard III of England|Richard III]], and has been the [[Patronage|patron]] of the [[Richard III Society]] since 1980.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/theroyalfamily/9903487/Duke-of-Gloucesters-concern-for-Richard-IIIs-dignity.html |title=Duke of Gloucester's concern for Richard III's 'dignity' |newspaper=The Telegraph |first= Tim |last=Walker|date=2 March 2013 |accessdate=24 March 2018}}</ref> He is also a member of the International Advisory Board of the [[Royal United Services Institute]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.royal.uk/charities-and-patronages?name=Royal+United+Services+Institute&mrf=10&field_themes_target_id=&field_world_region_value=|title=Charities and Patronages|publisher=The Royal Family|accessdate=24 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://rusi.org/event/duke-gloucester-lecture-series-flooding-and-british-armed-forces|title=The Duke of Gloucester Lecture Series: Flooding and the British Armed Forces|publisher=RUSI|date=12 November 2014|accessdate=24 March 2018}}</ref> Since 1972, the Duke has been a corporate member of the [[Royal Institute of British Architects]].<ref name=\"BBC-Isle\"/> He is also an honorary fellow of the [[Institution of Structural Engineers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.istructe.org/downloads/about-us/who-we-are/history-of-the-institution-of-structural-engineers.pdf|title=History of the Institution of Structural Engineers|publisher=Institution of Structural Engineers|accessdate=25 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nDuring 2009, the Duke became patron of the [[de Havilland Aircraft Museum|De Havilland Aircraft Heritage Centre]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/court-circular-may-16-jgvxmx2mlfl |title=Court Circular: May 16 |newspaper=The Times |date=15 May 2009|accessdate=24 March 2018}}</ref> in support of its bid to raise funds through private means and through a bid for Heritage Lottery Funding. Other patronages include: British Society of Soil Science,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.soils.org.uk/patron|title=Patron|publisher=British Society of Soil Science|accessdate=25 May 2018}}</ref> the [[International Council on Monuments and Sites]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.icomos-uk.org/events/50th-anniversary-conference/|title=ICOMOS-UK Launches Cultural Heritage Manifesto in 50th Anniversary Year|publisher=ICOMOS-UK|accessdate=25 May 2018}}</ref> [[Action on Smoking and Health]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ash.org.uk/media-and-news/ash-spokespeople/|title=ASH Spokespeople|publisher=ASH|accessdate=25 May 2018|date=August 2016}}</ref> [[British Association of Friends of Museums]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bafm.co.uk/home/about-bafm/|title=About BAFM|publisher=British Association of Friends of Museums|accessdate=25 May 2018}}</ref> British Mexican Society,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://britishmexicansociety.org.uk/bms-organisation/|title=BMS Organisation|publisher=British Mexican Society|accessdate=25 May 2018}}</ref> [[St Bartholomew's Hospital]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bartshealth.nhs.uk/news/a-royal-visit-for-st-bartholomews-1997|title=A Royal visit for St Bartholomew's|publisher=Barts Health NHS Trust|date=3 October 2017|accessdate=25 May 2018}}</ref> as well as numerous other organisations and charities.<ref name=\"Bio-Charity\">{{cite web|url=http://www.doi-archived.gov.mt/en/press_releases/2012/04/pr0819a.pdf|title=HRH The Duke of Gloucester KG GCVO|publisher=Gov.mt|accessdate=25 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2011, the Duke visited the [[Isle of Man]] to meet with the representative of [[Manx National Heritage]] and the Council of Cancer Charities.<ref name=\"BBC-Isle\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-isle-of-man-13960632|title=Duke of Gloucester to visit Isle of Man|publisher=BBC|date=29 June 2011|accessdate=25 May 2018}}</ref> On 8 November 2011, he opened the new Law School Building at the [[University of Hertfordshire]] on the de Havilland campus site of the former de Havilland Aircraft factory.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.whtimes.co.uk/news/royal_opening_of_university_of_hertfordshire_law_court_1_1121920 |title=Royal opening of University of Hertfordshire law court |work=Welwyn Hatfield Times |location=WGC| date=9 November 2011 |accessdate=24 March 2018 |first=Chris |last=Lennon}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 March 2013, the Duke represented Elizabeth II at [[Vatican City|the Vatican]] for the [[inauguration of Pope Francis]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/uk/cousin-stands-in-for-queen-at-pope-francis-crowning-8536058.html|title=Cousin stands in for Queen at Pope Francis 'crowning'|work=Evening Standard|date=15 March 2013 |accessdate=24 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 March 2015, the Duke visited the [[Royal School Dungannon]] in [[Dungannon]], [[County Tyrone]], [[Northern Ireland]] to celebrate their 400th anniversary since the founding of the school; presenting a commemorative plaque and raising an anniversary flag on the grounds.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/duke-of-gloucester-visits-northern-ireland|title=Duke of Gloucester visits Northern Ireland|date=11 March 2015|work=gov.uk|first=Andrew|last=Murrison|accessdate=24 March 2018}}</ref>  On 22 and 26 March 2015, the Duke represented the Queen at the ceremonies marking the [[Exhumation of Richard III of England|reburial and commemorations]] of [[Richard III]] in [[Leicester Cathedral]]. Richard III had held the title Duke of Gloucester before his ascension to the English throne.<ref name=orderofservice>{{cite web|title=Order of Service for the Reinterment of the Remains of King Richard III|url=http://www.channel4.com/microsites/R/RichardIII/Reinterment%2026%20March%20-%20PreServiceCopy.pdf|accessdate=26 March 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150326125617/http://www.channel4.com/microsites/R/RichardIII/Reinterment%2026%20March%20-%20PreServiceCopy.pdf|archivedate=26 March 2015|date=26 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2018, the Duke travelled to [[Malawi]] to attend the [[Commonwealth Day]] celebrations, and visited projects related to health services, wildlife, and climate change.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.royal.uk/duke-gloucester-visits-malawi|title=The Duke of Gloucester visits Malawi|publisher=The Royal Family|date=15 March 2018|accessdate=23 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbcafrica.com/apo/2018/03/09/royal-visit-the-duke-of-gloucester-to-visit-malawi-in-the-commonwealth-week/|title=Royal Visit: The Duke of Gloucester to visit Malawi in the Commonwealth Week|publisher=CNBC Africa|date=9 March 2018|accessdate=23 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Titles, styles, honours and arms==\n\n===Titles and styles===\n* 26 August 1944 \u2013 10 June 1974: His Royal Highness Prince Richard of Gloucester{{refn|As a patrilineal grandson of the [[British monarch]], he was styled ''His Royal Highness Prince Richard of Gloucester'' from birth. }}\n* 10 June 1974 \u2013 present: His Royal Highness The Duke of Gloucester\n\nHis Royal Highness Prince Richard Alexander Walter George, Duke of Gloucester, Earl of Ulster and Baron Culloden, Knight of the Most Noble Order of the Garter, Knight Grand Cross of the Royal Victorian Order, Grand Prior of the Most Venerable Order of the Hospital of Saint John of Jerusalem.\n\n===Honours===\n'''See also''': ''[[List of honours of the British Royal Family by country]]''\n\n* [[File:Ribbon - QE II Coronation Medal.png|45px]] 2 June 1953: [[Queen Elizabeth II Coronation Medal]]\n* [[File:Royal Victorian Order UK ribbon.png|45px]] 1974: [[Royal Victorian Order|Knight Grand Cross of the Royal Victorian Order]] (GCVO)\n* [[File:Order of St John (UK) ribbon.png|45px]] 1975: [[Venerable Order of Saint John|Bailiff Grand Cross of the Order of St John]] (GCStJ)<ref name=\"Bio-Charity\"/>\n* [[File:Service Medal of the Order of St John Ribbon.jpg|45px]] 1984: [[Service Medal of the Order of St John]] (with 5th bar(2 gold bars))\n* [[File:QEII Silver Jubilee Medal ribbon.png|45px]] 6 February 1977: [[Queen Elizabeth II Silver Jubilee Medal]]\n* [[File:Order of the Garter UK ribbon.png|45px]] 1997: [[Order of the Garter|Royal Knight of the Most Noble Order of the Garter]] (KG)\n* [[File:Queen Elizabeth II Golden Jubilee Medal ribbon.png|45px]] 6 February 2002: [[Queen Elizabeth II Golden Jubilee Medal]]\n* [[File:QEII Diamond Jubilee Medal ribbon.png|45px]] 6 February 2012: [[Queen Elizabeth II Diamond Jubilee Medal]]\n\n====Commonwealth====\n* [[File:Solomon islands indendence medal.png|45px]] 1978: [[Solomon Islands]] Independence Medal\n* [[File:Badge of Honour ribbon.png|45px]] 1980: [[Badge of Honour|Badge of Honour, New Hebrides]]<ref>{{cite book |editor-last=Mackay |editor-first=James |title=The Medal Yearbook 2004|year=2004|publisher=Token Publishing Ltd.|location=Devon, UK|isbn=9781870192620|page=236 |author=Mussell, John W.}}</ref> \n* [[File:Vanuatu Independence Medal ribbon.png|45px]] 1980: [[Vanuatu]] Independence Medal\n* [[File:Order of the Crown of Tonga - ribbon bar.gif|45px]] 1 August 2008: Knight Grand Cross with Collar of the [[Order of the Crown of Tonga]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://matangitonga.to/2008/08/01/royal-orders-presented-palace|title=Royal orders presented at Palace|publisher=Matangi Tonga Online|date=1 August 2008|accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref>\n* [[File:Ord.Star.SalomonIsland.png|45px]] 4 August 2008: [[Star of the Solomon Islands]] (SSI)<ref>[http://www.radioaustralia.net.au/programguide/stories/200808/s2323662.htm ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091028174146/http://www.radioaustralia.net.au/programguide/stories/200808/s2323662.htm |date=28 October 2009 }}</ref>\n\n====Foreign====\n* [[File:Order Sint Olaf 1 kl.png|45px]] 1973: Knight Grand Cross of the [[Order of St. Olav]]\n* [[File:MEX Orden del Aguila Azteca 2011 Banda Especial BAR.svg|45px]] 2015: Sash of Special Category of the [[Order of the Aztec Eagle]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://embamex.sre.gob.mx/reinounido/index.php/en/ver-comunicados/761-hrh-the-prince-of-wales-was-awarded-with-the-mexican-order-of-the-aztec-eagle|title=TRH THE PRINCE OF WALES AND THE DUCHESS OF CORNWALL AWARDED WITH THE MEXICAN ORDER OF THE AZTEC EAGLE|publisher=Official website of the Mexican Embassy in the United Kingdom|accessdate=11 April 2019}}</ref>\n** [[File:MEX Order of the Aztec Eagle 1Class BAR.png|45px]] 1973: Sash of the [[Order of the Aztec Eagle]]<ref>{{cite book|last=Olvera Ayes|first=David A |date=2011|title=La Orden Mexicana del \u00c1guila Azteca: apuntes para su historia|location=Mexico|publisher=Cuadernos del cronista|page=719|isbn=978-6070047213}}</ref>\n* [[File:SWE Order of the Polar Star (after 1975) - Commander Grand Cross BAR.png|45px]] 1975: Commander Grand Cross of the [[Order of the Polar Star]]\n* [[File:Ord.TriShaktiPatta.png|45px]] 1975: Member, 1st Class of the [[Order of Tri Shakti Patta]]\n* [[File:King Birendra Investiture Medal 1975.png|45px]] 24 February 1975: [[Kingdom of Nepal|Nepal]]ese Coronation Medal\n\n====Honorary military appointments====\n;{{Flagicon|AUS}} Australia\n* {{Flagicon|AUS|army}} Colonel-in-Chief, of the [[Royal Australian Army Education Corps]]<ref name=\"burke\">{{cite web\n| url         = http://www.burkespeerage.com/articles/peerage/page62-6h.aspx\n| title       = Burke's Peerage \u2013 The Royal Family \u2013 HRH The Duke of Gloucester\n| publisher=Burke's Peerage & Gentry and The Origins Network.\n| accessdate  =7 June 2011\n}}</ref>\n\n;{{Flagicon|NZL}} New Zealand\n* {{Flagicon|NZL|army}} Colonel-in-Chief of the [[Royal New Zealand Army Medical Corps]]\n\n;{{Flagicon|UK}} United Kingdom\n* {{Flagicon|UK|army}} Colonel-in-Chief, of the [[Royal Anglian Regiment]]<ref name=\"Bio-Charity\"/>\n* {{Flagicon|UK|army}} Colonel-in-Chief, of the [[Royal Army Medical Corps]]<ref name=\"Bio-Charity\"/>\n* {{Flagicon|UK|army}} Deputy Colonel-in-Chief, of the [[Royal Logistic Corps]]<ref name=\"Bio-Charity\"/>\n* {{Flagicon|UK|army}} Royal Colonel, of the 6th (V) Battalion, [[The Rifles]]<ref name=\"Bio-Charity\"/>\n* {{Flagicon|UK|army}} The Royal Honorary Colonel, of the [[Royal Monmouthshire Royal Engineers|Royal Monmouthshire Royal Engineers (Militia)]]<ref name=\"Bio-Charity\"/>\n* {{Flagicon|UK|air force}} Honorary [[Air Commodore]], of [[RAF Odiham]]<ref name=\"Bio-Charity\"/>\n* {{Flagicon|UK|air force}} Honorary Air Commodore, of [[No. 501 Squadron RAF|501 (County of Gloucester) Squadron]], [[Royal Auxiliary Air Force]], 16 June 2001.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=56269 |date= 10 July 2001 |page=8120 |supp=y }}</ref>\n* {{Flagicon|UK|air force}} Honorary [[Air Marshal]], [[Royal Air Force]], 1 September 1996.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=54519 |date= 9 September 1996 |page=12011 }}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n===Arms===\n{{Infobox COA wide\n|name = the Duke of Gloucester\n|image = Coat of Arms of Richard, Duke of Gloucester.svg\n|image size = \n|bannerimage = Royal Standard of Prince Richard, Duke of Gloucester.svg\n|badgeimage = \n|notes = The Duke of Gloucester's armorial bearings are based on the [[Royal coat of arms of the United Kingdom|Royal Arms]] as set down for descendants of George V. The following explains how his [[armorial bearings|Arms]] are different from those of The Queen and other members of The Royal Family.\n|coronet = [[Coronet|Coronet of a Grandchild of The Sovereign]]\n|year_adopted = 1962\n|crest = On a Coronet of children of other sons of the Sovereign, composed of four Crosses-patt\u00e9es alternated with four Strawberry Leaves, a Lion statant guardant [[Or (heraldry)|Or]], crowned with the like Coronet, and differenced with a Label as in the Arms.\n|torse = \n|helm = \n|escutcheon = \n|supporters = The Royal Supporters, differenced with a Coronet as in the Crest and Label as in the Arms.<ref name=\"burke\" />\n|compartment = \n|motto = \n|orders = The shield is surrounded by the [[Order of the Garter|Garter]] circlet, whose motto states:<br>'''HONI SOIT QUI MAL Y PENSE'''<br>''(Shame be to him who thinks evil of it)''\n|other_elements = Differences from the Royal Arms are a Label of five Points [[Argent (heraldry)|Argent]], the centre and two outer Points charged with a Cross [[Gules (heraldry)|Gules]], and the inner Points with a Lion passant guardant also Gules.\n\n[[File:VOSJ Grand Priory Coat of Arms.JPG|25px]] As Grand Prior, like other Bailiffs Grand Cross of the Most Venerable Order of St John of Jerusalem, HRH is entitled to augment the Arms of the [[Venerable Order of St John|Order]] in chief. \n|banner = The Duke of Gloucester's [[Heraldic flag|Standard (or Banner)]] displays his personal [[coat of arms|Arms]], granted in 1962.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.britishflags.net/dukeofgloucester.html |title=Duke of Gloucester |publisher=britishflags.net |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090201182908/http://www.britishflags.net/dukeofgloucester.html |archivedate=1 February 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> (In Scotland: [[File:Royal Standard of Prince Richard, Duke of Gloucester (in Scotland).svg|50px]])\n|badge = \n|symbolism = As in the Royal Arms of the United Kingdom, the first and fourth quarters represent [[Coat of arms of England|England]], the second [[Coat of arms of Scotland|Scotland]] and the third [[Coat of arms of Ireland|Ireland]].\n|previous_versions = \n}}\n\n==Issue==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name!! Birth!! colspan=\"2\" |Marriage!! Issue\n|-\n| [[Alexander Windsor, Earl of Ulster]] || 24 October 1974 || 22 June 2002 || Claire Booth || Xan Windsor, Lord Culloden<br>Lady Cosima Windsor\n|-\n| [[Lady Davina Windsor]] || 19 November 1977 || 31 July 2004<br /><small>Divorced 2018</small> || Gary Lewis || Senna Lewis<br>T\u0101ne Lewis\n|-\n| Lady Rose Gilman || 1 March 1980 || 19 July 2008 || George Gilman || Lyla Gilman<br>Rufus Gilman\n|}\n\n==Ancestry==\n{{ahnentafel\n|collapsed=yes |align=center\n|boxstyle_1=background-color: #fcc;\n|boxstyle_2=background-color: #fb9;\n|boxstyle_3=background-color: #ffc;\n|boxstyle_4=background-color: #bfc;\n|1= 1. '''Prince Richard, Duke of Gloucester'''\n|2= 2. [[Prince Henry, Duke of Gloucester]]\n|3= 3. [[Princess Alice, Duchess of Gloucester|Lady Alice Montagu Douglas Scott]]\n|4= 4. [[George V|George V of the United Kingdom]]\n|5= 5. [[Mary of Teck|Princess Mary of Teck]]\n|6= 6. [[John Montagu Douglas Scott, 7th Duke of Buccleuch]]\n|7= 7. [[Margaret Montagu Douglas Scott, Duchess of Buccleuch|Lady Margaret Bridgeman]]\n|8= 8. [[Edward VII|Edward VII of the United Kingdom]]\n|9= 9. [[Alexandra of Denmark|Princess Alexandra of Denmark]]\n|10= 10. [[Francis, Duke of Teck]]\n|11= 11. [[Princess Mary Adelaide of Cambridge]]\n|12= 12. [[William Montagu Douglas Scott, 6th Duke of Buccleuch]]\n|13= 13. [[Louisa Montagu Douglas Scott, Duchess of Buccleuch|Lady Louisa Hamilton]]\n|14= 14. [[George Bridgeman, 4th Earl of Bradford]]\n|15= 15. [[Ida Bridgeman, Countess of Bradford|Lady Ida Lumley]]\n}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[British prince]]\n* [[Venerable Order of St John|Most Venerable Order of the Hospital of St John of Jerusalem]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Hansard-contribs | mr-richard-windsor | the Duke of Gloucester }}\n* [https://www.royal.uk/the-duke-of-gloucester The Duke of Gloucester] at the Royal Family website\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-hou|[[House of Windsor]]|26 August|1944}}\n{{S-other|line}}\n{{S-bef|before=Arthur Chatto}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Line of succession to the British throne]]<!--NO position numbers after Chatto-->|creation=son of [[Prince Henry, Duke of Gloucester|Henry]], son of [[George V]]}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[Alexander Windsor, Earl of Ulster|Earl of Ulster]]}}\n{{S-reg|uk}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[Prince Henry, Duke of Gloucester|The Prince Henry]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=[[Duke of Gloucester]]|creation=5th creation|years=10 June 1974 \u2013 present}}\n{{S-inc|heir=[[Alexander Windsor, Earl of Ulster|Earl of Ulster]]|heir-type=Heir apparent}}\n{{S-prec|uk}}\n{{S-bef|before=[[David Armstrong-Jones, 2nd Earl of Snowdon|The Earl of Snowdon]]}}\n{{S-ttl|title=Gentlemen}}\n{{S-aft|after=[[Prince Edward, Duke of Kent|The Duke of Kent]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{UK Order of Precedence (Gentlemen)}}\n{{British princes}}\n{{Dukes of Gloucester}}\n{{Current British dukes}}\n{{Members of the Order of the Garter}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gloucester, Prince Richard, Duke of}}\n[[Category:1944 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century British people]]\n[[Category:21st-century British people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Magdalene College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Bailiffs Grand Cross of the Order of St John]]\n[[Category:British Anglicans]]\n[[Category:British landowners]]\n[[Category:Collars of the Order of the Aztec Eagle]]\n[[Category:Commanders Grand Cross of the Order of the Polar Star]]\n[[Category:Dukes of Gloucester]]\n[[Category:Earls of Ulster (1928)]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Royal Institute of British Architects]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the Society of Antiquaries of London]]\n[[Category:Honorary air commodores]]\n[[Category:House of Windsor|Richard, Duke of Gloucester]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People educated at Eton College]]\n[[Category:People from East Northamptonshire District]]\n[[Category:Princes of the United Kingdom|Richard, Duke of Gloucester]]\n[[Category:Royal Air Force air marshals]]\n[[Category:Architects from London]]\n[[Category:Barons Culloden]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the current Duke of Gloucester|the King previously known as Prince Richard, Duke of Gloucester|Richard III of England}}\n{{short description|Youngest grandchild of King George V and Queen Mary}}\n{{Use British English|date=October 2011}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox royalty\n| name         = Prince Richard\n| title        = [[Duke of Gloucester]] ([[#Titles, styles, honours and Arms|more]])\n| image        = The Duke of Gloucester (cropped).jpg\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date and age|1944|8|26|df=yes}}\n| birth_place  = St. Matthew's Hospital, [[Northampton]], England<ref name=Birth/>\n| full name    = Richard Alexander Walter George<ref name=\"sur\">As a titled royal, Richard needs no surname, but, when one is used, it is [[House of Windsor|Windsor]].</ref>\n| house        = [[House of Windsor|Windsor]]\n| suc-type     = Heir apparent\n| spouse       = {{marriage|[[Birgitte van Deurs]]|8 July 1972}}\n| issue        = {{plainlist|\n* [[Alexander Windsor, Earl of Ulster]]\n* [[Lady Davina Windsor]]\n* Lady Rose Gilman\n}}\n| father       = [[Prince Henry, Duke of Gloucester]]\n| mother       = [[Lady Alice Montagu Douglas Scott]]\n}}\n\n{{British Royal Family}}\n\n'''Prince Richard, Duke of Gloucester''', {{post-nominals|country=GBR|sep=,|size=100%|KG|GCVO|GCStJ}} (Richard Alexander Walter George; born 26 August 1944) is the youngest [[Descendants of George V and Mary of Teck|grandchild]] of [[King George V]] and [[Mary of Teck|Queen Mary]]. He practised as an architect until the death of his [[Prince William of Gloucester|elder brother]] placed him in direct line to inherit his [[Prince Henry, Duke of Gloucester|father]]'s [[dukedom of Gloucester]], which he inherited, as the second duke, in 1974. He is a paternal cousin of Queen [[Elizabeth II]], and currently 27th in the [[line of succession to the British throne]] as well as the first in line not descended from [[King George VI]].\n\n==Early life==\nPrince Richard was born on 26 August 1944 at 2:15 pm afternoon at St. Matthew\u2019s Hospital in [[Northampton]] .<ref name=Birth>{{London Gazette |issue= 36678 |date= 29 August 1944 |page=4017 }}</ref> His father was [[Prince Henry, Duke of Gloucester]], the third son of [[George V]] and [[Mary of Teck|Queen Mary]]. His mother was [[Princess Alice, Duchess of Gloucester]] (''n\u00e9e'' Lady Alice Montagu Douglas Scott), a daughter of the [[John Montagu-Douglas-Scott, 7th Duke of Buccleuch|7th Duke of Buccleuch]] and Lady Margaret Bridgeman. He was baptised at the [[Royal Chapel of All Saints]] in [[Windsor Great Park]] on 20 October 1944 by the retired [[Archbishop of Canterbury]], [[Cosmo Gordon Lang]].{{refn|His godparents were his paternal aunt, [[Queen Elizabeth The Queen Mother|Queen Elizabeth]], [[Princess Marie Louise of Schleswig-Holstein|Princess Marie Louise]] (his cousin), the [[Princess Alice, Countess of Athlone|Countess of Athlone]] (his cousin, for whom her daughter, [[Lady May Abel Smith]] stood [[proxy marriage|proxy]]), the [[Walter Montagu Douglas Scott, 8th Duke of Buccleuch|Duke of Buccleuch]] (his maternal uncle), the [[George Cambridge, 2nd Marquess of Cambridge|Marquess of Cambridge]] (his cousin), Lady Sybil Phipps (his maternal aunt), and [[Harold Alexander, 1st Earl Alexander of Tunis|General the Earl Alexander of Tunis]] (for whom his wife, then [[Margaret Alexander, Countess Alexander of Tunis|Lady Margaret Alexander]], stood proxy). Because of the War, newspapers did not identify the precise location of the christening, saying only that it took place at \"a private chapel in the country\".<ref name=\"times-1944\">[[The Times]], 21 October 1944</ref><ref name=\"times-1942\">[[The Times]], 5 August 1942</ref><ref name=\"Yvonne\">{{cite web|url=http://users.uniserve.com/~canyon/christenings.htm#Christenings |title=Yvonne's Royalty Home Page \u2013 Royal Christenings |publisher=users.uniserve.com |accessdate=30 April 2011}}</ref>}} When Richard was four months old, he accompanied his parents to [[Australia]], where his father served as [[Governor-General of Australia|Governor-General]] from 1945 to 1947. The family returned to [[Barnwell Manor]] in 1947, where Richard was largely raised.\n\nAt the time of his birth, he was fifth in the [[Succession to the British throne|line of succession to the throne]] and second in line to his father's [[duke]]dom, behind his brother, [[Prince William of Gloucester]]. He is 27th in line to the throne {{as of|2019|05|lc=y}}. William died in 1972 when the plane he was piloting crashed at Halfpenny Green near Wolverhampton. Richard then became heir apparent to his father's dukedom and inherited it two years later on the death of the first duke.\n\n== Education and career ==\n[[File:HRH The Duke of Gloucester Allan Warren.jpg|thumb|The Duke in 1989, by [[Allan Warren]]]]\n\nPrince Richard's early education took place at home, under the instruction of Rosamund Ramirez, who had also tutored young King [[Faisal II of Iraq]]; later, he attended [[Wellesley House School]] at [[Broadstairs]] and [[Eton College]].<ref name=\"Bio-Charity\"/> In 1963, he matriculated at [[Magdalene College, Cambridge]] where he read Architecture,<ref name=\"Bio-Charity\"/> graduating with the degree of [[Bachelor of Arts]] in June 1966; he [[proceed]]ed as [[Master of Arts (Oxbridge and Dublin)|MA (Cantab)]] in 1971.\n\nLater in 1966, straight after university, Prince Richard joined the Offices Development Group in the [[Ministry of Works (United Kingdom)|Ministry of Public Building and Works]] for a year of practical work. He returned to [[University of Cambridge|Cambridge]] in 1967, completing both parts of the [[Master's degree|Diploma in Architecture]] degree in June 1969. Upon passing his exams, he became a practising partner in Hunt Thompson Associates in London, an architectural firm.<ref name=\"worcester\">{{cite web|url=http://www.worcester.ac.uk/discover/hrh-prince-richard-the-duke-of-gloucester.html|title=HRH Prince Richard The Duke of Gloucester|year=2008|publisher=University of Worcester|accessdate=21 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nRichard intended to practise full-time as an [[architect]], but took on other responsibilities in 1972, after the death of his elder brother [[Prince William of Gloucester|Prince William]], who crashed his plane in a flying competition. Richard became [[heir apparent]] to his father's dukedom and had to take on additional family obligations and royal duties. He resigned his partnership and began representing his cousin, Elizabeth II, on royal duties.\n\nOn 10 June 1974, Prince Richard succeeded to his father's titles as ''[[Duke of Gloucester]], [[Earl of Ulster]], and [[Baron Culloden]]''. He was elected as a corporate member of the [[Royal Institute of British Architects]] (and FRIBA) in 1972. He is President of the Society of Architect Artists.<ref name=\"worcester\"/> He serves as a Commissioner of the Historic Building and Monuments Commission for England ([[English Heritage]]).\n\nThe Duke has been Patron of construction charity Construction Youth Trust<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.constructionyouth.org.uk/about-us/about-trust/construction-youth-trust-patron|title=Our Patron|publisher=Construction Youth Trust|accessdate=26 September 2016}}</ref> for many years. With his background in architecture, the Duke of Gloucester takes interest in the work of the Trust and frequently visits their projects, in addition to giving his name to their long standing Duke of Gloucester Young Achiever's Scheme Awards. The Duke is also patron of the Architects Benevolent Society.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.architectsjournal.co.uk/home/royal-patron-for-abs/142505.article|title=Royal Patron for ABS|date=6 March 2003|publisher=Architects Journal|last=|first=|website=www.architectsjournal.co.uk|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=24 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nHe is Royal Patron of the UK branch of the charity [[Habitat for Humanity]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.habitatforhumanity.org.uk/blog/2015/10/royal-patron-visits-hfh-hale-county/|publisher=Habitat for Humanity GB|title=Royal Patron visits HFH Hale County|accessdate=12 July 2016|date=30 October 2015}}</ref> Royal Patron of the St George's Society of New York,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stgeorgessociety.org/board.html|title=Board of Directors|publisher=St. George's Society of New York|accessdate=12 July 2016|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130413150308/https://www.stgeorgessociety.org/board.html|archivedate=24 March 2018}}</ref> and President of [[London Society (organisation)|The London Society]].\n\nA keen motorist, Prince Richard passed the [[Advanced Driving Test]] of the [[Institute of Advanced Motorists]], of which he was president for more than 32 years. On his appointment in 1971,<ref name=Motor197110>{{cite magazine | authorlink = Charles Bulmer (Ed) |title = Appointments Register|magazine=Motor| page =57| date = 9 October 1971}}</ref> it was recorded that the new President was \"currently [driving] an [[BMC ADO16|Austin 1300]]\", reflecting the modest image with which he has always been identified. He stood down as President in January 2005.<ref name=\"resignation\">[http://www.iam.org.uk/Pressroom/News_Releases/2005/nr0501.pdf Resignation Press Release] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050517124347/http://www.iam.org.uk/Pressroom/News_Releases/2005/nr0501.pdf |date=17 May 2005 }}</ref>\n\nOn 10 April 2008, the Duke was installed as Founding Chancellor of the [[University of Worcester]] in a ceremony at Worcester Cathedral. A former teacher training college, the institution was raised to university status in 2006.<ref name=\"worcester\"/>\n\n==Marriage and family==\n[[File:Duke and Duchess of Glocstrer.jpg|thumb|right|The Duke and Duchess of Gloucester]]\nOn 8 July 1972, Prince Richard married the [[Denmark|Danish]]-born [[Birgitte van Deurs]] in St Andrew's Church at [[Barnwell, Northamptonshire|Barnwell]], [[Northamptonshire]]; they have three children:\n\n*[[Alexander Windsor, Earl of Ulster]], born 24 October 1974 at [[St Mary's Hospital, London]]. He married [[Claire Booth]] in 2002. The couple have two children.\n*[[Lady Davina Windsor]], born 19 November 1977 at [[St Mary's Hospital, London]]. She married Gary Lewis in 2004. They divorced in 2018. They have two children.\n*Lady Rose Gilman, born 1 March 1980 at [[St Mary's Hospital, London]]. She married George Gilman in 2008. The couple have two children.\nThe Duke and Duchess of Gloucester's official residence is at [[Kensington Palace]] in London.<ref>{{cite web|title=Royal residences: Kensington Palace |url=http://www.royal.gov.uk/TheRoyalResidences/KensingtonPalace/Today.aspx |publisher=Official website of the Royal Family |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130726232558/http://www.royal.gov.uk/TheRoyalResidences/KensingtonPalace/Today.aspx |archivedate=26 July 2013 }}</ref> They have leased their private home, [[Barnwell Manor]], since 1994.\n\n==Activities==\n\nThe Duke of Gloucester, accompanied by the Duchess, represented his cousin [[Elizabeth II]] at the [[Solomon Islands]] independence celebrations on 7 July 1978.<ref>[http://www.solomonencyclopaedia.net/biogs/E000475b.htm Gloucester, Duke and Duchess of], Solomon Islands Historical Encyclopaedia 1893-1978, Retrieved 2019-02-06.</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.solomontimes.com/news/solomon-islands-to-get-a-royal-visit/1954 |title=Solomon Islands to Get a Royal Visit' |publisher=Solomon Islands Times |date=17 June 2008 |accessdate=6 February 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 April 2008, the Duke of Gloucester was officially installed as inaugural [[Chancellor (education)|Chancellor]] of the [[University of Worcester]] at a ceremony in [[Worcester Cathedral]]. In this role, the [[Prince]] officiates at degree ceremonies and major events, as well as promoting the University overseas.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.worc.ac.uk/discover/hrh-prince-richard-the-duke-of-gloucester.html|title=HRH Prince Richard The Duke of Gloucester|publisher=University of Worcester|accessdate=25 May 2018}}</ref> The Duke carried out the first of these duties on 5 and 6 November 2008 at the Graduation Award Ceremonies.\n\nThe Duke is also patron of the [[Severn Valley Railway]] and the [[Pestalozzi International Village|Pestalozzi International Village Trust]]. He is also a patron of the [[British Homeopathic Association]], a charity dedicated to the study, research and promotion of [[homeopathy]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.britishhomeopathic.org/charity/bha-events/reception-with-the-duke-of-gloucester/|title=Royal support for homeopathy|publisher=British Homeopathic Association|accessdate=25 May 2018|date=March 2016}}</ref> He shares a name with another Duke of Gloucester, [[Richard III of England|Richard III]], and has been the [[Patronage|patron]] of the [[Richard III Society]] since 1980.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/theroyalfamily/9903487/Duke-of-Gloucesters-concern-for-Richard-IIIs-dignity.html |title=Duke of Gloucester's concern for Richard III's 'dignity' |newspaper=The Telegraph |first= Tim |last=Walker|date=2 March 2013 |accessdate=24 March 2018}}</ref> He is also a member of the International Advisory Board of the [[Royal United Services Institute]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.royal.uk/charities-and-patronages?name=Royal+United+Services+Institute&mrf=10&field_themes_target_id=&field_world_region_value=|title=Charities and Patronages|publisher=The Royal Family|accessdate=24 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://rusi.org/event/duke-gloucester-lecture-series-flooding-and-british-armed-forces|title=The Duke of Gloucester Lecture Series: Flooding and the British Armed Forces|publisher=RUSI|date=12 November 2014|accessdate=24 March 2018}}</ref> Since 1972, the Duke has been a corporate member of the [[Royal Institute of British Architects]].<ref name=\"BBC-Isle\"/> He is also an honorary fellow of the [[Institution of Structural Engineers]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.istructe.org/downloads/about-us/who-we-are/history-of-the-institution-of-structural-engineers.pdf|title=History of the Institution of Structural Engineers|publisher=Institution of Structural Engineers|accessdate=25 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nDuring 2009, the Duke became patron of the [[de Havilland Aircraft Museum|De Havilland Aircraft Heritage Centre]]<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/court-circular-may-16-jgvxmx2mlfl |title=Court Circular: May 16 |newspaper=The Times |date=15 May 2009|accessdate=24 March 2018}}</ref> in support of its bid to raise funds through private means and through a bid for Heritage Lottery Funding. Other patronages include: British Society of Soil Science,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.soils.org.uk/patron|title=Patron|publisher=British Society of Soil Science|accessdate=25 May 2018}}</ref> the [[International Council on Monuments and Sites]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.icomos-uk.org/events/50th-anniversary-conference/|title=ICOMOS-UK Launches Cultural Heritage Manifesto in 50th Anniversary Year|publisher=ICOMOS-UK|accessdate=25 May 2018}}</ref> [[Action on Smoking and Health]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ash.org.uk/media-and-news/ash-spokespeople/|title=ASH Spokespeople|publisher=ASH|accessdate=25 May 2018|date=August 2016}}</ref> [[British Association of Friends of Museums]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bafm.co.uk/home/about-bafm/|title=About BAFM|publisher=British Association of Friends of Museums|accessdate=25 May 2018}}</ref> British Mexican Society,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://britishmexicansociety.org.uk/bms-organisation/|title=BMS Organisation|publisher=British Mexican Society|accessdate=25 May 2018}}</ref> [[St Bartholomew's Hospital]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bartshealth.nhs.uk/news/a-royal-visit-for-st-bartholomews-1997|title=A Royal visit for St Bartholomew's|publisher=Barts Health NHS Trust|date=3 October 2017|accessdate=25 May 2018}}</ref> as well as numerous other organisations and charities.<ref name=\"Bio-Charity\">{{cite web|url=http://www.doi-archived.gov.mt/en/press_releases/2012/04/pr0819a.pdf|title=HRH The Duke of Gloucester KG GCVO|publisher=Gov.mt|accessdate=25 May 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2011, the Duke visited the [[Isle of Man]] to meet with the representative of [[Manx National Heritage]] and the Council of Cancer Charities.<ref name=\"BBC-Isle\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-isle-of-man-13960632|title=Duke of Gloucester to visit Isle of Man|publisher=BBC|date=29 June 2011|accessdate=25 May 2018}}</ref> On 8 November 2011, he opened the new Law School Building at the [[University of Hertfordshire]] on the de Havilland campus site of the former de Havilland Aircraft factory.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.whtimes.co.uk/news/royal_opening_of_university_of_hertfordshire_law_court_1_1121920 |title=Royal opening of University of Hertfordshire law court |work=Welwyn Hatfield Times |location=WGC| date=9 November 2011 |accessdate=24 March 2018 |first=Chris |last=Lennon}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 March 2013, the Duke represented Elizabeth II at [[Vatican City|the Vatican]] for the [[inauguration of Pope Francis]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.standard.co.uk/news/uk/cousin-stands-in-for-queen-at-pope-francis-crowning-8536058.html|title=Cousin stands in for Queen at Pope Francis 'crowning'|work=Evening Standard|date=15 March 2013 |accessdate=24 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn 11 March 2015, the Duke visited the [[Royal School Dungannon]] in [[Dungannon]], [[County Tyrone]], [[Northern Ireland]] to celebrate their 400th anniversary since the founding of the school; presenting a commemorative plaque and raising an anniversary flag on the grounds.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/duke-of-gloucester-visits-northern-ireland|title=Duke of Gloucester visits Northern Ireland|date=11 March 2015|work=gov.uk|first=Andrew|last=Murrison|accessdate=24 March 2018}}</ref>  On 22 and 26 March 2015, the Duke represented the Queen at the ceremonies marking the [[Exhumation of Richard III of England|reburial and commemorations]] of [[Richard III]] in [[Leicester Cathedral]]. Richard III had held the title Duke of Gloucester before his ascension to the English throne.<ref name=orderofservice>{{cite web|title=Order of Service for the Reinterment of the Remains of King Richard III|url=http://www.channel4.com/microsites/R/RichardIII/Reinterment%2026%20March%20-%20PreServiceCopy.pdf|accessdate=26 March 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150326125617/http://www.channel4.com/microsites/R/RichardIII/Reinterment%2026%20March%20-%20PreServiceCopy.pdf|archivedate=26 March 2015|date=26 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2018, the Duke travelled to [[Malawi]] to attend the [[Commonwealth Day]] celebrations, and visited projects related to health services, wildlife, and climate change.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.royal.uk/duke-gloucester-visits-malawi|title=The Duke of Gloucester visits Malawi|publisher=The Royal Family|date=15 March 2018|accessdate=23 March 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbcafrica.com/apo/2018/03/09/royal-visit-the-duke-of-gloucester-to-visit-malawi-in-the-commonwealth-week/|title=Royal Visit: The Duke of Gloucester to visit Malawi in the Commonwealth Week|publisher=CNBC Africa|date=9 March 2018|accessdate=23 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Titles, styles, honours and arms==\n\n===Titles and styles===\n* 26 August 1944 \u2013 10 June 1974: His Royal Highness Prince Richard of Gloucester{{refn|As a patrilineal grandson of the [[British monarch]], he was styled ''His Royal Highness Prince Richard of Gloucester'' from birth. }}\n* 10 June 1974 \u2013 present: His Royal Highness The Duke of Gloucester\n\nHis Royal Highness Prince Richard Alexander Walter George, Duke of Gloucester, Earl of Ulster and Baron Culloden, Knight of the Most Noble Order of the Garter, Knight Grand Cross of the Royal Victorian Order, Grand Prior of the Most Venerable Order of the Hospital of Saint John of Jerusalem.\n\n===Honours===\n'''See also''': ''[[List of honours of the British Royal Family by country]]''\n\n* [[File:Ribbon - QE II Coronation Medal.png|45px]] 2 June 1953: [[Queen Elizabeth II Coronation Medal]]\n* [[File:Royal Victorian Order UK ribbon.png|45px]] 1974: [[Royal Victorian Order|Knight Grand Cross of the Royal Victorian Order]] (GCVO)\n* [[File:Order of St John (UK) ribbon.png|45px]] 1975: [[Venerable Order of Saint John|Bailiff Grand Cross of the Order of St John]] (GCStJ)<ref name=\"Bio-Charity\"/>\n* [[File:Service Medal of the Order of St John Ribbon.jpg|45px]] 1984: [[Service Medal of the Order of St John]] (with 5th bar(2 gold bars))\n* [[File:QEII Silver Jubilee Medal ribbon.png|45px]] 6 February 1977: [[Queen Elizabeth II Silver Jubilee Medal]]\n* [[File:Order of the Garter UK ribbon.png|45px]] 1997: [[Order of the Garter|Royal Knight of the Most Noble Order of the Garter]] (KG)\n* [[File:Queen Elizabeth II Golden Jubilee Medal ribbon.png|45px]] 6 February 2002: [[Queen Elizabeth II Golden Jubilee Medal]]\n* [[File:QEII Diamond Jubilee Medal ribbon.png|45px]] 6 February 2012: [[Queen Elizabeth II Diamond Jubilee Medal]]\n\n====Commonwealth====\n* [[File:Solomon islands indendence medal.png|45px]] 1978: [[Solomon Islands]] Independence Medal\n* [[File:Badge of Honour ribbon.png|45px]] 1980: [[Badge of Honour|Badge of Honour, New Hebrides]]<ref>{{cite book |editor-last=Mackay |editor-first=James |title=The Medal Yearbook 2004|year=2004|publisher=Token Publishing Ltd.|location=Devon, UK|isbn=9781870192620|page=236 |author=Mussell, John W.}}</ref> \n* [[File:Vanuatu Independence Medal ribbon.png|45px]] 1980: [[Vanuatu]] Independence Medal\n* [[File:Order of the Crown of Tonga - ribbon bar.gif|45px]] 1 August 2008: Knight Grand Cross with Collar of the [[Order of the Crown of Tonga]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://matangitonga.to/2008/08/01/royal-orders-presented-palace|title=Royal orders presented at Palace|publisher=Matangi Tonga Online|date=1 August 2008|accessdate=26 May 2018}}</ref>\n* [[File:Ord.Star.SalomonIsland.png|45px]] 4 August 2008: [[Star of the Solomon Islands]] (SSI)<ref>[http://www.radioaustralia.net.au/programguide/stories/200808/s2323662.htm ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091028174146/http://www.radioaustralia.net.au/programguide/stories/200808/s2323662.htm |date=28 October 2009 }}</ref>\n\n====Foreign====\n* [[File:Order Sint Olaf 1 kl.png|45px]] 1973: Knight Grand Cross of the [[Order of St. Olav]]\n* [[File:MEX Orden del Aguila Azteca 2011 Banda Especial BAR.svg|45px]] 2015: Sash of Special Category of the [[Order of the Aztec Eagle]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://embamex.sre.gob.mx/reinounido/index.php/en/ver-comunicados/761-hrh-the-prince-of-wales-was-awarded-with-the-mexican-order-of-the-aztec-eagle|title=TRH THE PRINCE OF WALES AND THE DUCHESS OF CORNWALL AWARDED WITH THE MEXICAN ORDER OF THE AZTEC EAGLE|publisher=Official website of the Mexican Embassy in the United Kingdom|accessdate=11 April 2019}}</ref>\n** [[File:MEX Order of the Aztec Eagle 1Class BAR.png|45px]] 1973: Sash of the [[Order of the Aztec Eagle]]<ref>{{cite book|last=Olvera Ayes|first=David A |date=2011|title=La Orden Mexicana del \u00c1guila Azteca: apuntes para su historia|location=Mexico|publisher=Cuadernos del cronista|page=719|isbn=978-6070047213}}</ref>\n* [[File:SWE Order of the Polar Star (after 1975) - Commander Grand Cross BAR.png|45px]] 1975: Commander Grand Cross of the [[Order of the Polar Star]]\n* [[File:Ord.TriShaktiPatta.png|45px]] 1975: Member, 1st Class of the [[Order of Tri Shakti Patta]]\n* [[File:King Birendra Investiture Medal 1975.png|45px]] 24 February 1975: [[Kingdom of Nepal|Nepal]]ese Coronation Medal\n\n====Honorary military appointments====\n;{{Flagicon|AUS}} Australia\n* {{Flagicon|AUS|army}} Colonel-in-Chief, of the [[Royal Australian Army Education Corps]]<ref name=\"burke\">{{cite web\n| url         = http://www.burkespeerage.com/articles/peerage/page62-6h.aspx\n| title       = Burke's Peerage \u2013 The Royal Family \u2013 HRH The Duke of Gloucester\n| publisher=Burke's Peerage & Gentry and The Origins Network.\n| accessdate  =7 June 2011\n}}</ref>\n\n;{{Flagicon|NZL}} New Zealand\n* {{Flagicon|NZL|army}} Colonel-in-Chief of the [[Royal New Zealand Army Medical Corps]]\n\n;{{Flagicon|UK}} United Kingdom\n* {{Flagicon|UK|army}} Colonel-in-Chief, of the [[Royal Anglian Regiment]]<ref name=\"Bio-Charity\"/>\n* {{Flagicon|UK|army}} Colonel-in-Chief, of the [[Royal Army Medical Corps]]<ref name=\"Bio-Charity\"/>\n* {{Flagicon|UK|army}} Deputy Colonel-in-Chief, of the [[Royal Logistic Corps]]<ref name=\"Bio-Charity\"/>\n* {{Flagicon|UK|army}} Royal Colonel, of the 6th (V) Battalion, [[The Rifles]]<ref name=\"Bio-Charity\"/>\n* {{Flagicon|UK|army}} The Royal Honorary Colonel, of the [[Royal Monmouthshire Royal Engineers|Royal Monmouthshire Royal Engineers (Militia)]]<ref name=\"Bio-Charity\"/>\n* {{Flagicon|UK|air force}} Honorary [[Air Commodore]], of [[RAF Odiham]]<ref name=\"Bio-Charity\"/>\n* {{Flagicon|UK|air force}} Honorary Air Commodore, of [[No. 501 Squadron RAF|501 (County of Gloucester) Squadron]], [[Royal Auxiliary Air Force]], 16 June 2001.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=56269 |date= 10 July 2001 |page=8120 |supp=y }}</ref>\n* {{Flagicon|UK|air force}} Honorary [[Air Marshal]], [[Royal Air Force]], 1 September 1996.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=54519 |date= 9 September 1996 |page=12011 }}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n===Arms===\n{{Infobox COA wide\n|name = the Duke of Gloucester\n|image = Coat of Arms of Richard, Duke of Gloucester.svg\n|image size = \n|bannerimage = Royal Standard of Prince Richard, Duke of Gloucester.svg\n|badgeimage = \n|notes = The Duke of Gloucester's armorial bearings are based on the [[Royal coat of arms of the United Kingdom|Royal Arms]] as set down for descendants of George V. The following explains how his [[armorial bearings|Arms]] are different from those of The Queen and other members of The Royal Family.\n|coronet = [[Coronet|Coronet of a Grandchild of The Sovereign]]\n|year_adopted = 1962\n|crest = On a Coronet of children of other sons of the Sovereign, composed of four Crosses-patt\u00e9es alternated with four Strawberry Leaves, a Lion statant guardant [[Or (heraldry)|Or]], crowned with the like Coronet, and differenced with a Label as in the Arms.\n|torse = \n|helm = \n|escutcheon = \n|supporters = The Royal Supporters, differenced with a Coronet as in the Crest and Label as in the Arms.<ref name=\"burke\" />\n|compartment = \n|motto = \n|orders = The shield is surrounded by the [[Order of the Garter|Garter]] circlet, whose motto states:<br>'''HONI SOIT QUI MAL Y PENSE'''<br>''(Shame be to him who thinks evil of it)''\n|other_elements = Differences from the Royal Arms are a Label of five Points [[Argent (heraldry)|Argent]], the centre and two outer Points charged with a Cross [[Gules (heraldry)|Gules]], and the inner Points with a Lion passant guardant also Gules.\n\n[[File:VOSJ Grand Priory Coat of Arms.JPG|25px]] As Grand Prior, like other Bailiffs Grand Cross of the Most Venerable Order of St John of Jerusalem, HRH is entitled to augment the Arms of the [[Venerable Order of St John|Order]] in chief. \n|banner = The Duke of Gloucester's [[Heraldic flag|Standard (or Banner)]] displays his personal [[coat of arms|Arms]], granted in 1962.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.britishflags.net/dukeofgloucester.html |title=Duke of Gloucester |publisher=britishflags.net |url-status = dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090201182908/http://www.britishflags.net/dukeofgloucester.html |archivedate=1 February 2009 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> (In Scotland: [[File:Royal Standard of Prince Richard, Duke of Gloucester (in Scotland).svg|50px]])\n|badge = \n|symbolism = As in the Royal Arms of the United Kingdom, the first and fourth quarters represent [[Coat of arms of England|England]], the second [[Coat of arms of Scotland|Scotland]] and the third [[Coat of arms of Ireland|Ireland]].\n|previous_versions = \n}}\n\n==Issue==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Name!! Birth!! colspan=\"2\" |Marriage!! Issue\n|-\n| [[Alexander Windsor, Earl of Ulster]] || 24 October 1974 || 22 June 2002 || Claire Booth || Xan Windsor, Lord Culloden<br>Lady Cosima Windsor\n|-\n| [[Lady Davina Windsor]] || 19 November 1977 || 31 July 2004<br /><small>Divorced 2018</small> || Gary Lewis || Senna Lewis<br>T\u0101ne Lewis\n|-\n| Lady Rose Gilman || 1 March 1980 || 19 July 2008 || George Gilman || Lyla Gilman<br>Rufus Gilman\n|}\n\n==Ancestry==\n{{ahnentafel\n|collapsed=yes |align=center\n|boxstyle_1=background-color: #fcc;\n|boxstyle_2=background-color: #fb9;\n|boxstyle_3=background-color: #ffc;\n|boxstyle_4=background-color: #bfc;\n|1= 1. '''Prince Richard, Duke of Gloucester'''\n|2= 2. [[Prince Henry, Duke of Gloucester]]\n|3= 3. [[Princess Alice, Duchess of Gloucester|Lady Alice Montagu Douglas Scott]]\n|4= 4. [[George V|George V of the United Kingdom]]\n|5= 5. [[Mary of Teck|Princess Mary of Teck]]\n|6= 6. [[John Montagu Douglas Scott, 7th Duke of Buccleuch]]\n|7= 7. [[Margaret Montagu Douglas Scott, Duchess of Buccleuch|Lady Margaret Bridgeman]]\n|8= 8. [[Edward VII|Edward VII of the United Kingdom]]\n|9= 9. [[Alexandra of Denmark|Princess Alexandra of Denmark]]\n|10= 10. [[Francis, Duke of Teck]]\n|11= 11. [[Princess Mary Adelaide of Cambridge]]\n|12= 12. [[William Montagu Douglas Scott, 6th Duke of Buccleuch]]\n|13= 13. [[Louisa Montagu Douglas Scott, Duchess of Buccleuch|Lady Louisa Hamilton]]\n|14= 14. [[George Bridgeman, 4th Earl of Bradford]]\n|